ting the world of work and encouraging those i</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">n receipt of benefits to manage their finances in similar fashion to those who are working. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">2.2 However we are aware that </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">he direct payment demonstration projects are already showing an increase in rent arrears, despite </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">organisations </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">increasing </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">their </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">staff resources to manage the process. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">The fear is therefore that l</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">andlords will not be able to replicate this level of intensive management across their entire stock, with a real concern that arrears levels will increase further.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> The risks are potentially</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> greater within a supported housing environment as the incidence of v</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ulnerable tenants</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> will be greater and such tenants may be the </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">least likely to be able to maintain rent payments to their landlord. The Local Support Services Framework sets out extensive </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">measures to assist those most vulnerable and needing support to cope, but introduces new bureaucracy and processes</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We believe that landlords, in consultation with their tenants, should be able to agree how rent is paid to them. Most supported housing</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> providers will </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">work to promote the independence of their tenants and will recognise when it is appropriate to have rent paid direct to them, bypassing the tenant, and when it makes sense for the tenant to take personal responsibility. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">2.4 Should the cur</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">rent commitment to direct payments remain then t</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">he ability for direct payments to revert back to the landlord at a two month trigger point is welcome and necessary; </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">as is the intention to allow potential reversion to be discussed after one month. B</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ut for m</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">any vulnerable tenants </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">the uncertainty and anxiety caused during these initial weeks </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">could be avoided entirely </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">if the landlord and the tenant could agree at the outset how best rent was to be paid.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">3. Household benefit cap</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">3.1 Allowing those living within</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> supported accommodation to come within the total benefit cap, whilst ignoring </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">actual </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">help with housing costs when calculating the cap </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">for anyone in exempt accommodation, is extremely complicated.  In practice, those living in exempt accommodation are ofte</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">n disabled and by ignoring both their housing costs and disability benefits, the majority fall well </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">below </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">the cap. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">However the</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> current definition of exempt accommodation remains far from clear</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">his means that those living in supported accommodation which is not considered exempt </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">face having</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> their total benefits capped</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">; even though their circumstances may differ very little from those in exempt accommodation.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">3.2 We feel strongly that it is time </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">for the definition of exempt accommodation to be clarified for providers, local authorities and tenants. W</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">e also feel that w</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">hatever the final definition, </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">the cap would be greatly simplified by omitting all supported</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> housing as this would ensure that those </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">of working age living in supported housing can receive the full support of the welfare system which they need.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Social</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> sector size criteria</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">4.1 Evidence of application of the social sector size criteria so far indicates that this is counter productive </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">and cannot achieve the stated aim of better use of housing stock. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">4.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">particularly concerned that the criteria penalise </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">both </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">disabled couples and single claimants who require an additional bedroom for health reasons – whether this be a medical need</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> to sleep separately, or to accommodate essential medical equipment. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">his is often likely to be the case in supported housing</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> as those with such medical needs also have wider support needs</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">; and as much supported housing is not currently considered to be ex</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">empt</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> from the size criteria</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">, vulnerable disabled people are disadvantaged. Indeed, many </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">not need high levels of other support</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">, but</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">do</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> actually need the extra bedroom</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> as a form of support to maintain their independence and well being.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">4.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">Since 2006 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">Department of Health funding for new extra care developments has specified that properties should have 3 habitable rooms. This is still the case for Home and Communities Agency funding. New schemes are funded and developed on this bas</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">. The Department for</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> Work and Pension will now potentially say that this is too large for the household's needs and the resident will see a reduction in their housing benefit entitlement due to the size criteria restrictions</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">4.4 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">For many disabled people in the social sector</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">, downsizing therefore will not be an option. However those who cannot afford to retain the spare bedroom may be forced to look to alternative accommodation in the private sector which may not </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ultimately be cheaper, and which will not reduce the benefits b</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ill. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">The lack of suitable alternative accommodation is a major concern. The availability of one bedroom properties puts severe restrictions and limitation on the ability for people to downsize. People are often stuck in a situation where there housing bene</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">fit entitlement is restricted as the property is deemed too large for their needs but there is no smaller accommodation available.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">5</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We are concerned about adults with disabilities and are unsure as to why disabled children are not expected to have to s</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">hare a bedroom whereas a recent </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">igh </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ourt judgement has said that disabled adults are expected to share a bedroom. Often with older people, even if they wanted to share a bedroom, this is not always practical a</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">s a result of health problems. We realise tha</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">t this</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> recent judicial review does not support our contention that those with a proven disability and medical need for an extra bedroom should be able to receive help with the cost of this</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">. However we remain convinced</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> that it is still appropriate </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">that the </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">implications and impact upon vulnerable disabled claimants should be reconsidered</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> as part of this review</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Localised</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> council tax support</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">5.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We all </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">work across a large number of local authorit</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">un</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">aware of any which have not adhered to the </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">guidance that vulnerable claimants should not receive less council tax support than they did previously under Council Tax Benefit.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> This is welcome; however we fear that as local authority budgets become more restricted, the lack of a national system will i</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ncreasingly lead to local variation and the ‘postcode lottery’ principle.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">5.2 Without a national demand led system, local circumstances and budgetary pressures will inevitably mean that disabled people and those in supported accommodation will eventually </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">find that the level of help they can expect with council tax varies between areas, irrespective of their personal circumstances. This will undermine the support that they receive elsewhere, and the safety net will become increasingly disjointed and fragmen</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ted.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6. T</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">reatment of housing costs within Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">major concerns concentrate on the following areas –</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> service charge provisions; benefit overlaps when moving home; temporary absence provisions; waiting periods; and notification of housing cost awards.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Service charge provisions are restricted in comparison to Housing Benefit.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">The principles appear to assume that the majority of working age claimants occupy straightforward property with very little in the way of services apart from fairly standard items such as refuse collection, car parking, gardening. The new service charge pr</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ovisions do not sufficiently reflect the complexity of </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">supported housing and the additional facilities this may provide.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We hope that the provisions for window cleaning costs are not replicated in any service charge provision for older people, as we consid</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">er that it is unhelpful for anyone living in sheltered housing to be expected to </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">clean</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> windows at any level.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of any provision for overlap of benefit when moving home.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">It is extremely difficult for those on the lowest incomes to pay for a notice period as well as the rent for a new property when moving home. The majority of disabled people and those needing supported housing do not move on a whim, but because they need m</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ore suitable accommodation. Without help with housing costs, many will be unable to accept the </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">accommodation they badly need and local strategies to meet specific housing need will not be met.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">This lack of provision to meet housing costs for a notice peri</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">od is also likely to affect those wishing to downsize to avoid social sector size criteria penalties. We do not believe that discretionary housing payment funding will remain sufficient to cover this, and that these provisions act as a deterrent to the aim</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> of achieving better use of housing stock nationally.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">6.4 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">A standard six month provision for absence from home.</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">A blanket provision for absence from home for any reason provides administrative simplicity, but lacks fairness</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">. Replacing the present 13 week</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> absence rule within Housing Benefit with six months for Universal Credit, provides an over generous opportunity for those who are not genuinely occupying the property as their home; whilst simultaneously penalising the sick and disabled who may need to sp</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">end an extended time in hospital or nursing care. Such claimants will be forced into a choice between rent arrears or not receiving the nursing care and support they need. Ultimately for some this will lead to increased dependence upon state resources at a</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> far higher cost.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">6.5</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> T</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">he decision to apply the waiting period to the whole Universal Credit award.   </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">understand that this will only apply to claimants who are expected to work and have full work-related requirements; but it is unclear how this might a</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ffect vulnerable and disabled claimants. There are many with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">that</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> are expected and able to work, and who wish to do so</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">; however they may find themselves placed in the full work requirement group. Many will already find that they receive less </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">help </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">through premiums within Universal Credit, and having to wait an extra 7 days before receiving any housing costs will place an additional obstacle in their way.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">Overall we consider that a total waiting period of up to 38 days before a first payment is</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt"> made will penalise those on the lowest incomes who are most in need of help at the start of their claim. This does not accurately reflect the world of work for many low paid workers who are not usually expected to work their first week without getting pai</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">d at all; and who are often paid weekly rather than salaried monthly. No one on a salary is expected to wait that long for their first payment. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">An increase in those on very low incomes who are desperately short of money at the start of their claim, will </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">lead to an increase in requests for help via local welfare provision – at a time when local schemes are already providing less assistance due to restricted funding. </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">Scarce resources will therefore be further pressured by the poorest having nowhere else to </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">turn for assistance during the extended waiting period. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">strongly </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">feel that the precise detail of how this provision will apply to vulnerable and disabled people </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">needs further careful consideration. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">6.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Notification of amount of housing costs. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">Although Universal Credit is meant to replicate a wage by being paid as a single payment, we see no purpose in not clearly identifying actual amounts towards housing costs within the award. We hope that everyone will receive notification of awards which c</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">learly show how much help is being provided towards housing costs</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">, as this will assist in supporting claimants towards managing their own payments.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">7. Implications of future changes for older people</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">7.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ll three </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">providers </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">appreciate that how support for </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">housing costs is delivered for older people is outside the scope of this inquiry; but we do not want to miss the opportunity to comment on this. We urge that very careful consideration is given to how help towards housing costs within Pension Credit is det</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">ermined, and how this aligns with Universal Credit provisions.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">7.2 We consider that the issues of eligible service charges, overlap of benefit for two homes, and period of absence from home for hospital or respite care, would pose significant problems for </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">older people should these provisions be replicated within Pension Credit. There would be consequences for older people being able to downsize from family homes</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">, as well as the inability to move to smaller suitable supported accommodation. This would lead t</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">o many being unable to remain living </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">independently for longer, with consequent increased social care costs. We remain convinced that such consequences would be unintended and counter productive.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">7.3 In conclusion, w</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">e are aware that the DWP are currently r</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">eviewing the definition of 'exempt accommodation' status for housing benefit purposes. The current definition states that the landlord or a person acting on their behalf also provides the claimant with care, support or supervision. The government is pushin</span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">g the personalisation agenda, whereby people are encouraged to receive direct payments rather than care packages organised by Social Services. With personalisation, the landlord is less like to be involved in the provision of care as individuals will take </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">responsibility for organising their own care.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">It is very important </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">the new definition of exempt accommodation that this is factored in, particularly in relation to extra care properties. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">26 </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September </span><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans Unicode'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>